NIWA-SCENZ Trends
Temporal trend maps generated for each month (01-12), season (Sum., Aut., Win., Spr.), and year (overall) using the Sen slope method. Statistical significance was determined using the Mann-Kendall Z statistic and p-values. Monthly anomaly maps eliminate seasonality in trend analysis. Trends, expressed as both absolute magnitude and as a percentage of the climatology, are presented per decade. Trend direction assessment procedures are applied, resulting in maps indicating confidence in slope direction, expressed as "Likelihood" categories rather than just distinguishing from zero.

Caveats: Linear trends, assessed from July 2002 onwards, should be interpreted cautiously when predicting future patterns due to the exclusion of interannual and multi-year non-linear shifts. Assessing ecological and/or management significance is challenging, given the lack of accepted importance thresholds for New Zealand coastal waters.

This is a companion application to an MPI funded project (SEA2022-12) and report: "Cyclone impacts on fisheries". Specific objectives include hydrodynamic and sediment modelling coupled with observations on the spatial and temporal extent of river stormflow plumes. Future updates to include all NIWA-SCENZ products are planned.
